-- PRESS DIGEST- Financial Times - Jan 21
-- 
-- Mon Jan 20, 2014 08:39PM EST
-- None



Jan 21 (Reuters) - The following are the top stories in the Financial Times. Reuters has not verified these stories and does not vouch for their accuracy.

Headlines  AIRBUS CHIEF TO CHALLENGE EUROSCEPTICS (http://link.reuters.com/jur26v)  RETAILERS JOIN GROWING IPO SHOPPING LIST (http://link.reuters.com/dur26v)  MORRISON TREASURER SUSPENDED OVER INSIDER DEALING PROBE (http://link.reuters.com/fur26v)  REGULATORS TO PROBE CO-OP'S FINANCES IN A FRESH BLOW TO BANK (http://link.reuters.com/gur26v)  CONVIVIALITY RETAIL LOSING HOPE OVER PRICE FLOOR FOR ALCOHOL (http://link.reuters.com/kur26v)   Overview  Airbus Group <AIR.PA> is expected to challenge British eurosceptics and make a case in favour of UK's membership of the European Union. The aerospace company told the Financial Times that the UK as part of the EU is an economic model that works "extremely well".  Discount retailer Poundlands and Pets at Home are expected to float by early February, sources told the Financial Times. Poundlands may seek a valuation of 700 million pounds to 800 million pounds, while Pets at Home may be valued at 1.5 billion pounds.  WM Morrison <MRW.L> suspended group treasurer Paul Coyle, arrested in December by the Financial Conduct Authority in connection with an insider trading case, according to sources. Coyle has not been charged for any offence as yet.  The Financial Reporting Council will probe auditor KPMG's book-keeping at the Co-operative Bank, which has been hit by a capital shortfall of 1.5 billion pounds and a drugs scandal involving its ex-chairman.